    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-06-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-06-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="1058"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1058">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">895.63 Or 4/48</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1340</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-06-10">June 10,
                            1935</date>.<lb/>[Received June 29.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to this Embassy’s
                    despatch No. 992, dated October 2, 1934,<note n="1" xml:id="d1058fn1">
                        <ref target="frus1934v03#pg_824">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1934, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 824</ref>.</note> in regard to the
                    demand of the taxation officials of the Chosen Government General to examine the
                    books of the Oriental Consolidated Mining Company, for the purpose of assessing
                    income tax upon the employees of the Company, and to the Department’s
                    instruction No. 645, dated December 3, 1934,<note n="2" xml:id="d1058fn2">
                        <ref target="frus1934v03#pg_826">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid</hi>., p. 826</ref>.</note> authorizing the
                    American Consul at Seoul to address a letter to the Chosen Government General on
                    the subject.</p>
                <p>According to a letter from the American Consul at Seoul dated May 17, 1935, (a
                    copy of which was sent to the Department<note n="3" xml:id="d1058fn3">Not
                        printed.</note>) the Chosen Government General refuses to relinquish its
                    claim to the right to examine the books for income taxation purposes, and the
                    Consul suggests that, in order to avoid unpleasantness, the Company might keep a
                    separate ledger of disbursements for salaries and exhibit this book voluntarily
                    to the taxation authorities. If the Department perceives no objection to this
                    procedure, the Embassy will instruct the Consul to suggest the plan to the
                        Company.<note n="4" xml:id="d1058fn4">Instruction No. 828, August 26, to the
                        Ambassador in Japan stated: “The Department perceives no objection to the
                        proposed suggestion, and you are therefore authorized to instruct the Consul
                        at Seoul to make this suggestion to the Oriental Consolidated Mining
                        Company.”</note>
                </p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Joseph C. Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
